<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910603-0047</DOCNO><DOCID>910603-0047.</DOCID><HL>   International:   Toyota Expands   Its U.S. Facilities   For Research Work   ----   Special to The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>06/03/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7E</SO><CO>   TOYOY</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>AUTOMOBILES (AUT)INTERNATIONAL TRADE NEWS (TRD)</IN><NS>TRADE ISSUES (TRD)</NS><RE>FAR EAST (FE)JAPAN (JA)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)</RE><LP>   TOKYO -- Toyota Motor Corp. said it is expanding its U.S.research and development facilities as part of its efforts tocreate fully integrated operations in the U.S.   Thursday, the company's U.S. Randamp;D arm, Toyota TechnicalCenter U.S.A. Inc., opened a $46 million prototype-vehicleevaluation facility in Torrance, Calif. Major featuresinclude hot and cold chambers for testing climate-controlsystems and performance under extreme environmentalconditions, along with an anechoic chamber to measure noiseand vibration.</LP><TEXT>   TTC began construction Friday of a $110 million vehicleproving facility 45 miles northwest of Phoenix, Ariz. Theproving ground, used to evaluate the overall performance ofvehicles at high speeds and extreme temperatures, isscheduled for operation in 1993.   Also Friday, Toyota's U.S. design arm in Newport Beach,Calif., opened a major addition, effectively doubling itssize. The $19 million expansion of Calty Design Research Inc.includes studios for analyzing color designs and buildingclay models, and a system for transferring three-dimensionalinformation from models to an electronic drawing machine.   On Thursday, TTC will open a $41 million evaluationlaboratory for parts, materials and vehicles at its technicalcenter in Ann Arbor, Mich. The laboratory will handle testingof U.S.-made parts and materials for use in Toyota's NorthAmerican operations and for export to Japan.</TEXT></DOC>